# Plan: SEO Boost — JSON-LD Structured Data

## Context

The Amytis blog has solid OG/Twitter metadata but zero JSON-LD structured data. Adding
JSON-LD `Article`, `Book`, and `BreadcrumbList` schemas unlocks Google rich results
(article carousels, breadcrumb trails in SERPs) and improves crawlability. No new npm
packages are needed — structured data is pure JSON injected via a `<script>` tag.

---

## Files

| Action | Path |
|--------|------|
| **Create** | `src/lib/json-ld.ts` |
| **Modify** | `src/app/posts/[slug]/page.tsx` |
| **Modify** | `src/app/[slug]/[postSlug]/page.tsx` |
| **Modify** | `src/app/books/[slug]/page.tsx` |
| **Modify** | `src/app/books/[slug]/[chapter]/page.tsx` |
| **Modify** | `src/app/flows/[year]/[month]/[day]/page.tsx` |

Existing utilities reused:
- `getPostsListUrl()` — `src/lib/urls.ts:29` — builds the posts listing URL
- `getPostUrl(post)` — `src/lib/urls.ts:20` — canonical post URL (handles custom basePath)
- `resolveLocale()` — `src/lib/i18n.ts` — already imported in all target pages

---

## Step 1 — Create `src/lib/json-ld.ts`

Pure TypeScript module (no React, no side-effects). Exports four builder functions that
accept pre-resolved data and return a `SchemaGraph` object ready for `JSON.stringify`.

### Schema injection pattern (Next.js App Router)
```tsx
<script
  type="application/ld+json"
  dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}
/>
```

### Output structure (all pages use `@graph`)
```json
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [ ...one or more schema nodes... ]
}
```

### Exported functions & params

```ts
export function buildPostJsonLd(params: {
  post: { title, excerpt, date, authors, tags, coverImage?, series? };
  postUrl: string;          // absolute
  seriesTitle?: string;     // if post belongs to a series
  seriesUrl?: string;       // absolute URL to the series page
  siteTitle: string;
  siteUrl: string;          // no trailing slash
  defaultOgImage: string;
}): SchemaGraph

export function buildBookJsonLd(params: {
  book: { title, excerpt?, date, authors, coverImage?, slug };
  bookUrl: string;
  siteTitle: string;
  siteUrl: string;
  defaultOgImage: string;
}): SchemaGraph

export function buildBookChapterJsonLd(params: {
  chapter: { title, excerpt?, slug };
  book: { title, slug, date, authors };
  chapterUrl: string;
  bookUrl: string;
  siteTitle: string;
  siteUrl: string;
}): SchemaGraph

export function buildFlowJsonLd(params: {
  flow: { title, excerpt, date, tags };
  flowUrl: string;
  siteTitle: string;
  siteUrl: string;
  defaultOgImage: string;
}): SchemaGraph
```

### Schema per page type

**Posts / Flows → `BlogPosting` + `BreadcrumbList`**
- `BlogPosting`: headline, description, url, datePublished, dateModified, author[], publisher (Organization), image (ImageObject), keywords (comma-joined tags), mainEntityOfPage
- Breadcrumb: `Home → Series (if any, else Posts listing) → Post title`

**Books → `Book` + `BreadcrumbList`**
- `Book`: name, description, url, datePublished, author[], publisher, image
- Breadcrumb: `Home → Books → Book title`

**Book chapters → `Article` + `BreadcrumbList`**
- `Article`: headline, description, url, datePublished, author[], publisher, isPartOf (Book)
- Breadcrumb: `Home → Books → Book title → Chapter title`

**Flows** — `BlogPosting` only (no breadcrumb; the page already has a rich visual breadcrumb)

### Image resolution rule
Mirror existing `generateMetadata` logic: use `coverImage` only if it's an external HTTP URL; otherwise fall back to `defaultOgImage` (always absolute).

---

## Step 2 — `src/app/posts/[slug]/page.tsx`

Add after `seriesTitle` is resolved (line 123):
```ts
